      "role": "user",
      "content": "ok got it. so the light reactions happen in the thylakoid and make the ATP/NADPH, and then the Calvin cycle uses them to turn CO2 into sugar in the stroma. it seems like a lot of tiny moving parts working together perfectly. is there any other specific part of that cycle that usually shows up on exams? like maybe how the cycle actually resets itself?",
      "source": "evaluator",
      "targeted_response_start": "",
      "beast_baseline": "ok got it. so the light reactions happen in the thylakoid and make the ATP/NADPH, and then the Calvin cycle uses them to turn CO2 into sugar in the stroma. it seems like a lot of tiny moving parts working together perfectly. is there any other specific part of that cycle that usually shows up on exams? like maybe how the cycle actually resets itself?",
